{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657426/1923112201/0610.xml":{"full_text":"CQBUDGE FOR TAX\nSLASH. SAYS BORAH\ns\nIdaho Senator Sees Presi\ndent Before Issuing State\nment on Proposal.\nSenator Borah of Idaho conferred\n\u2022with President Coolidge today regard-\nIrtg the tax cut proposal, and. accord-1\niag to comment made by the senator j\nafterward, \u201cthe President is deeply j\ninterested in reducing taxes.\u201d That\nwas as much as the senator wished to\nsay regarding the President\u2019s talk with\nhim today.\nSenator Borah intimated that he took\ntip with the President certain features\ncontained in a statement he has pre- j\njtaved dealing with the tax reduction j\nsubject and which he proposed to make\npublic later.\nSenator Ernst, republican, of Ken\n-1 uoky also saw the President today and\nrMscussed fax reduction. The senator\nsaid emphatically that the people of\nthe country want tax reduction, they\ndeserve it. and that he is strongly in\nfavor of it. He said he would support\nany legislation that would lift the bur\nden from the people. He said also that\ntie was unalterably opposed to a sol-\ndiers\u2019 bonus.\nGets Massachusetts Data.\nRepresentative Robison of Ken\ntucky, who accompanied the senator\nto the White House, would not com\nmit himself regarding tax reduction\nor a bonus.\nThe President today was given some\ndefinite idea of what the party work\ners In his home state are doing in\norganization work preparatory to the\nformal opening of the 19-4 campaign\nby Prank Poss, republican state\nchairman of Massachusetts. He told\nthe President that the party was\nmaking groat strides in organization\nwork and the methods adopted to in\ncrease the registration of voters,\nespecially among women, are meeting\nwith success.\nBy means of index cards Chairman\nPoss was able to give the President\nencouraging data. He assured the\nPresident that republicans of the\nstate arc solidly behind him and that\nthe people, irrespective of party, are\neager for some form of tax reduction.\nDelegate* Mentioned.\nHe discussed also with the Presi\ndent the matter of electing delegates\nfrom Massachusetts to the next re\npublican convention, saying that the\nleaders were of the opinion that\namong those to be thus honored\nshould be Senator Bodge, Secretary\nof War Weeks, Speaker Gillett, Wil\nliam N. Butler, republican national\ncommitteeman, and some women of\nprominence.\nWilliam H. Miller, former repub\nlican state chairman of Ohio and still\nactive In party politics in that state,\nwhile discussing Ohio politics with\nthe President today said that the\nparty organization there was in splen\ndid shape and the prevailing senti\nment was strong for the President\nfor 1924. This sentiment, he said, has\nbeen intensified by the feeling in\n>hio that President Coolidge has kept\nfaith with Harding policies.\nMiller See* President.\nCol. Thomas W. Miller, alien prop\nerty custodian, took up with the\n1 \u2018resident important ls-ues affecting\nthe future policy of his department.\nF. W. Straus, New York financier,\nwho recently returned from Europe,\nwhere he made an extensive study of\neconomic conditions, in a conference\nwith the President said that, while\nhe did not believe the United States\nCould escape eventual moral respon\nsibilities as a world stabilizer, he\ndi<l not believe the present a pro\npitious time to participate in the Eu\nropean situation, owing to widely va\nried points of view existing among\nthe different countries.\nMr. Sfraus expressed himself as being\nmuch impressed with the President\u2019s\ndeep interest in current business de\nvelopment and with his comprehensive\nunderstanding of the business outlook.\nAs a recognized authority on conditions\nm the bbilding industry he gave the\nPresident an. optimistic report on the\nbuilding situation in the nation today.\n\u2022fibers who saw the President today\nwere Bonis Marshall of New York,\nSenators Dale of Vermont, and Spencer\nof .Missouri, ajtd Warren Olney of Cali\nfornia.\nNAMED TO WEST POINT, j\nPresident Appoints T. J. Moran,\nDistrict Boy.\nThomas J. Moran. 4603 Georgia ave- i\nnue. this city, has been appointed bv\nPresident Coolidge a cadet-at-large at J\nthe United States Military Academv.\nsubject to examination March 4. with\na view to admission July 1.\nCongressional appointments as ca\ndets at, the Academy from the eighth\ndistrict of Virginia include Wilbur\nS. Hlnman. Jr., Falls Church, as first 1\nalternate; Shedrlck C. Anderson, Ar\neola, as second alternate: Michael M.\nMcNamee Rosslyn; Marion G. Pohl,\nAlexandria, as first alternate, and\nKobert If. Housol, Clarendon, as sec\nond alternate.\nI Home j\n\"Quality is Important\u2014Fit is Impcrathc'\\ I\nCorrection for Swollen I\nTwisted Ankles\nnd \u201cRun-in\u201d\nHeels\nug more unsightly\nDn is not difficult. 9\n111 i;DMO;v.',. W.\\.s ORIG-^\u00b0 eS Jv Oil\nINAL ARCH INSTEP jf/\n1 BRACE HIGH AND LOW\nI SHOES are Corrective and I\nj|| yet they are \u201csmart\u201d shoes,\nj A steel brace is built into W|,\nH| the shoe. It supports the f\nU foot comfortably. The shoe \\o** Aorunnktx\nclutches the heel\u2014fits the V arch iiini\nankle like a stocking. It\nrelieves and corrects foot y|\n\u2014Consult our Professional pJa\" I\nShoe Fitters about the re- v\nquirements of your feet. Oxfords to Match\nEDMONSTON CO. I\n_ (Incorporated)\n|!i 1 <4 p Sfrrrf Advisers and Authorities on\ntoo** r oireer AII Foot Troubles\nANDREW BETZ. Manager\nill *'c HUH\nMOVE TO PREVENT\nJAILING CONTROLLER\nAttorneys for Craig, New York,\nMay Try to Have Case\nReopened\n\nB.r the Associated Press.\nXUW YORK, November 22. j\u2014Law\nyers are busily engaged today on a\nplan whereby they hope to save Con\ntroller Charles\nH tfSufq Federal Judge Ju\n-1 Bus M. Mayer and\nj v W the\nR3BE|h iwipli he reopening of\nbe c:ls\nC. L. CRAIG. that details would\nnot be made\nknown until a definite decision was\nreached.\nMr. Craig still 